Copy constructor

Default copy constructor:
• the compiler generates it automatically if you don't provide one
• performs shallow copy

Below is an example of copy constructor.
	Because we don't have our own copy constructor, 
	we learn that Default copy constructor is called provided by the compiler

You will also learn that this line should not be mistaken for Copy Assignment operator, because of equal sign.
	BasicNumber num2 = num1
Why?
	see code.

When can a copy constructor be used?
	- when the object is initialized
	- Typical use case is when a DEEP copy of an object is required,
		when object has dynamically allocated member variables.
		i.e member variables that point to data on the HEAP.
	- when an object is returned by value from a function
	- when an object is passed by value as an argument to a function
//--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

using namespace std;

class BasicNumber
{
public:
        int n;

        BasicNumber (int set_n )
        {
            cout << "Base Param constructor is called." << endl;
            n = set_n;
        }
};

int main()
{
    BasicNumber num1(7);

    cout << "num1: " << num1.n << endl;

    BasicNumber num2 = num1;  -->// Don't confuse this with Copy assignment operator.
									// Copy constructor is called if you are initializing an object
									// notice num1 already exists. we are initializing num2 with num1
    
    cout << "num2: " << num2.n << endl;
    
    return 0;
}
